title: For Sale/Trade:  38 s and w made in 1900,1962 browning nomad
postcontent:
great piece of history,aside from a few tweaks here and there this is the start of a gun line that has lasted over 100 years and still the most popular revolver design made.called the model of 1889 i think? its the 1rst hand ejector revolver. serial puts it made  in 1900(gun forums helped me find this out),no front lug is further proof of its age.they added the lug around 1903.was nickel plated but there isnt much finish left.engineer changes and dates are visable and so is the smith and wesson makings.it functions like it should.timed right.there is a little play in the yoke(which is probly a reason they added the front lug)but the back of the cylinder locks tight.gun this old shouldnt be takin the the range anyway but it will fire.looking for 250 for it.

title: For Sale:  Model CZ 241 16-Gauge Shotgun; 3-shot semi-auto with magazine "well"
postcontent:
The original CZ (Ceska Zbrojovka; Strakonice); Model CZ 241 16-Gauge Shotgun; 3-shot semi-auto with magazine "well." Markings: "CZ"; "N"; 48 (manufactured in 1948). Designed for 2-9/16" shells, which presents challenges today. I have been using 2-3/4" shells with it to hunt dove.  It has been my favorite dove gun because of its balance and light weight.

Model History: This model made in a large production numbers from 1946-1950; developed during WWII by the group of the Czech designers, namely Ladislav Schmitmayer, Vaclav Jindra and Jindrich Brejcha in CZ plant at Uhersky Brod. They received help from an another six gunsmiths working at that time in R&D shop. Work was done secretly as an above mentioned group kept development of CZ 241 from the Germans, who occupied the factory at that time.  During the years 1942-1944 the CZ 241 underwent a heavy testing and the tests proved that CZ 241 is an excellent shotgun.  In the last test, before full production was introduced, the gun was successfully fired eighty thousand times without one problem.  After liberation of former Czechoslovakia, the CZ 241 went into a full production in 1946.  It was produced in three gauges: 12, 16, 20.  Weight of the shotgun is 2,90 kg.  Production started in a factory at City of Strakonice, but very shortly after, the production of the CZ 241 was shifted to CZ's plant in Uhersky Brod. In years 1946-1947 the receiver of CZ 241 were made from light alloy material sourced from the propellers of the American planes shot down over the area by the Germans during the war.  The barrels were made of an excellent material which was used to make the barrels for an aircraft machine gun MG 131.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Model 1842 Musket (Civil War Era)
postcontent:
This is an authentic Springfield Model 1842 smoothbore .69 caliber muzzle loading musket.  It was likely used in the Civil War.  This rifle is in good to very good condition for its age and includes the bayonet.  The ramrod is missing, but reproduction ramrods are readily available and original ramrods are often available through antique gun sellers.

This was the first regulation percussion ignition musket made at the national armories. It was also the last smoothbore U.S. arm made in .69 caliber and the first U.S. weapon made at both Springfield and Harpers Ferry.   The Model 1842 was the first small arm produced in the U.S. with fully interchangeable, machine-made parts. About 172,000 Model 1842 muskets were produced at the Springfield national armory between 1844 and 1855.  

This gun has the following stampings on the steel:
Lock:  1850 and U.S. eagle with arrows
Breech:  1852
Barrel:  V over P with an eagle head
Butt plate:  U.S. 51

The metal has brown patina throughout with some minor pitting.  The lock, trigger and hammer operate.  The wood is in good condition with typical dings, scratches and handling marks.  The wood butt also has “PM” etched in it, which is a typical soldier marking of military rifles of the era.  This rifle appears to be all original and historically correct.  It has not been cleaned, polished, repaired or altered in order to preserve its value.

The value of this rifle is in its historical significance, age and condition.  The highly visible markings on the steel hardware combined with the bayonet make this a rare find and worthy of adding to a collection or using in Civil War reenactments.

 A great Christmas gift for the Civil War enthusiast!

I will ship within the continental U.S. where legal for $30.  Buyer assumes all responsibility for legal ownership and use.  Due to the age of this gun and percussion firing mechanism, no FFL is required.

$1099  Or Near Offer.  Sorry, I'm not looking for trades.
